<br>
I'll admit it, I still find this game fun and I have well over a year /played on my bard.  Even so, you'd have to be blind not to see the faults and discrepancies that pervade the EQ of today.  The average raid guild has a window of about 4-6 hours in which to kill things, anything that spawns beyond that window will either pass to the next time zone or will roll over to the next day.  Any mob that rolls over to the next day is automatically going to give the Japanese guilds the first chance.  After them, the Europeans have the next most advantageous time zones.  Should they fail to kill the mob, next comes the East coast of the US.  Anyone on the West coast of the US has a massive built-in disadvantage when raiding, which is a bit unfair in a game that's based pretty much 100% on raiding.  Decry it any way you like, this is simply a fact.  People in uberguilds tend to want to keep this fact hush-hush for obvious reasons and this board has become decidedly &quot;uber&quot; over the last few years so I won't be the least bit surprised when people disagree with this.  But this is exactly why focusing on the raid is losing them so very many customers.  I'm in excellent gear and I've progressed fairly far into GoD but I still feel this is true.<br>
<br>
Sorry about my first post, but going into this much detail for absolutely nothing since I know darn well it's the uberguilds which have killed EQ but that I will find no agreement on this board for that viewpoint seemed pointless.<br>
<br>
-FF<br>
